title: Plane with five passengers crashes into shopping centre in Melbourne | Metro News

organizations.name: metro news toby meyjes for metro.co.uk

text:
Toby Meyjes for Metro.co.uk Monday 20 Feb 2017 10:48 pm The crash sent huge plumes of smoke into the air (Picture: 9 News Melbourne) 
A small charter plane has crashed into a shopping centre in Melbourne sending huge plumes of smoke into the air. 
At least five people were thought to have been on the light aircraft when it collided with DFO shopping centre in Essendon, in Melbourne’s north-west. Leaders of these countries say the press is the 'enemy of the people' 
The crash occurred shortly before 9am local time but there was no word on casualties. 
Earlier reports had suggested an air ambulance was involved in the crash but this was later discounted by Ambulance Victoria. 
A spokeswoman for Victoria Police told new.com.au emergency services are responding to the crash. Driving by a possible plane crash at #Essendon Airport and DFO pic.twitter.com/JpSCKbgxHN 
She said: ‘At this stage we do not have information regarding possible casualties and police are currently evacuating the area’ 
Metropolitan Fire Brigade has advised motorists to avoid the area due to the extensive smoke. 
— Thomas Maggs (@Tsm042) February 20, 2017 #BREAKING : An Air Ambulance has crashed into the DFO factory outlet near Essendon Airport in Melbourne. #TMS7 pic.twitter.com/uLJuGUumKu
